          "title": "The measuring line interrupted — human planning superseded by divine promise",
          "body": "The vision opens with Zechariah seeing a man holding a measuring line, on his way to survey Jerusalem's dimensions (2:1-2). The scene would resonate immediately with Zechariah's post-exilic audience: Jerusalem was still largely rubble, and the question of the city's future size and security was intensely practical. Measuring was the precondition for rebuilding walls. But before the survey begins, an angelic messenger intercepts with a counter-word from God (2:3-5): Jerusalem will be so full of people and animals that no wall could contain it, and — more radically — walls will be unnecessary because God Himself will be the wall.\n\nThe interruption is the theological hinge of the entire vision. It does not merely modify the architectural plan; it replaces the architectural category. Human security logic begins with measurement, proceeds to construction, and trusts the finished wall. Divine security logic begins with God's own being — 'I will be a wall of fire around her' (2:5) — and requires no construction. The wall is not a thing God builds; the wall IS God. The same theological move appears in Isaiah 26:1 ('God will appoint salvation for walls and ramparts') and Psalm 125:2 ('As the mountains surround Jerusalem, so the Lord surrounds His people'). Zechariah's vision places the post-exilic community in that same tradition."
