          "body": "Three times in this short chapter a divine figure declares 'the Lord of hosts has sent Me' (2:8, 9, 11). The speaker is distinguished from the Lord of hosts who sends Him, yet He speaks with God's own authority, makes God's own promises ('I will dwell in your midst,' 2:10), and accomplishes God's own purposes. He is sent 'after glory' — meaning, in pursuit of God's own glory-reputation, as its agent and embodiment. The repetition is deliberate and the distinction is real: this is not a figure of speech but a genuine differentiation within the divine identity.\n\nOrthodox interpreters from Calvin onward have recognized here a pre-incarnate appearance of the second person of the Trinity — the Angel of the Lord who appears elsewhere in the OT (Genesis 16:7-13; Exodus 3:2-6; Judges 6:11-22) as one who is both sent by God and identified with God. The pattern is identical to the Son's self-description in John 17:3, 8, 18 ('You sent Me') — sent by the Father, yet sharing the Father's divine being. The chapter does not resolve the distinction systematically; that is the NT's work. But it refuses to collapse it. The Messenger who says 'I am coming and I will dwell in your midst' (2:10) is the One whom John 1:14 will declare 'became flesh and dwelt (*eskēnōsen*) among us' — the same tabernacling vocabulary, the same divine agent, the same dwelling-in-the-midst."
