        "body": "The opening scene is architecturally concrete. A man with a *chevel* (measuring line) is on his way to survey Jerusalem — to determine its width (*rochav*) and length (*orekh*). The measuring vocabulary belongs to the world of practical urban reconstruction: you cannot build walls without knowing the perimeter. For a community still clearing rubble and laying foundations (Zechariah's contemporaries were midstream in the project Ezra-Nehemiah chronicles), the scene is entirely recognizable.\n\nThe angelic interruption at verse 3-4 does not merely slow the survey — it renders the entire measuring category obsolete. The divine counter-word announces that Jerusalem's population and livestock will overflow any wall that could be built. But the reason for walllessness is not merely demographic; it is theological. God declares: 'I will be a wall of fire around her' (2:5). The protection is not something God provides in addition to walls; it is God's own being as the city's perimeter. The image reaches back to the wilderness pillar of fire (Exodus 13:21; 14:20) — the same divine presence that made the Egyptian army helpless at the sea is now promised as the permanent perimeter of the eschatological Jerusalem.\n\nThe second half of verse 5 — 'I will be the glory in her midst' — is the chapter's most theologically freighted clause. The *kavod* (glory) had departed Jerusalem in Ezekiel's vision (Ezekiel 10-11) — it was the book's most devastating moment, more catastrophic than the Babylonian siege itself. Zechariah's promise reverses that departure: the glory is not merely returning to the temple's Holy of Holies but to the city's *midst* (*tavekh*) — filling the center of the entire urban space. The eschatological city is the temple.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Perazah* (unwalled settlement, 2:4) — an open-country village, the opposite of a fortified city. The promise is not that Jerusalem will upgrade its walls but that the category of 'walled city' will become irrelevant. *Kavod* (glory) — the weighty, luminous, manifest presence of God, His honor made visible. The same word appears in 2:8 in the mission-statement of the divine Messenger. *Chomah* (constructed wall) and *esh* (fire) — in God's economy, the wall He builds is His own fiery presence, not hewn stone."
