        "body": "The transition from vision to oracle at verse 6 is marked by the double *hoy* — 'Ho! Ho!' — a prophetic alarm-cry that demands immediate response. The double repetition intensifies urgency: this is not an invitation but a command with a deadline. The exiles addressed are still living 'with the daughter of Babylon' (2:7), comfortable enough in Mesopotamia that they have not joined the returnees of Zerubbabel's expedition. The summons is to flee before the coming judgment, not merely to consider returning.\n\nVerse 8 introduces the chapter's most theologically dense clause: 'He who touches you, touches the apple of His eye.' The *bavah* — the pupil of the eye — is used only here in the entire Hebrew Bible for this expression (Deuteronomy 32:10 uses a different word, *ishon*). The image is not sentimental; it is anatomical and reflexive. The pupil blinks before a conscious decision is made; the reflex is instantaneous and irresistible. Nations that plunder Israel provoke an immediate, irresistible divine response. The implication is that the suffering of the exile, while sovereignly permitted, was not God's disinterest — any attack on His people attacks His most sensitive point.\n\nThe reversal of verse 9 is total: the nations that made Israel their plunder will become plunder for their own servants. The social inversion is deliberate — not merely defeated, but enslaved to those they themselves enslaved. The recognition formula that closes verse 9 — 'Then you will know that the Lord of hosts has sent Me' — is a recurring Ezekielian phrase (Ezekiel uses it over sixty times). Its function here is epistemic: the fulfillment of the judgment will certify both the Messenger's divine sending and the Lord's sovereignty over history.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Bavah* (pupil of the eye, 2:8) — unique OT occurrence of this specific lexeme for this image; the rarity underscores the precision and intimacy of the claim. *Shalach* (sent Me) — the passive construction in all three occurrences (2:8, 9, 11) emphasizes the Sender's authority behind the Messenger's mission. *Shalal* (plunder, 2:8-9) — the same word appears as both verb (the nations 'plundered' Israel) and noun (Israel's enemies become 'plunder'). The reversal is lexical as well as historical."
