        "body": "The oracle's movement from judgment (2:8-9) to joy (2:10) mirrors the classic prophetic pattern: the nations are judged so that the city can sing. The imperative to 'sing for joy and be glad' (*roni v'simchi*, 2:10) is the same pair that appears in Isaiah 12:6, 54:1, and Zephaniah 3:14 — the exuberant response to the arriving Lord. Here the warrant for the joy is stated with exceptional directness: 'I am coming and I will dwell in your midst' (*shakhan b'tavekh-ekh*, 2:10). The verb *shakhan* is the cognate of *mishkan* — God is about to tabernacle among His people again, as He did in the wilderness.\n\nVerse 11 extends the promise beyond ethnic Israel in language that would have been startling in a post-exilic prophetic context: 'Many nations will join themselves to the Lord in that day and will become My people.' The verb *lavah* (join themselves) is the same verb from which the name Levi is etymologically associated — to attach oneself closely, to cling (Genesis 29:34). These nations are not becoming secondary members of a Zion-centered community; they are becoming the Lord's people — *am* — the covenant designation par excellence. The Gentile mission of Acts is not a theological emergency measure; it is the scheduled outcome of promises like this one.\n\nVerse 12's designation of the land as *admat ha-qodesh* — 'the holy land' — its only occurrence in the entire Hebrew Bible, reframes the territorial question. The land is not primarily Israel's national possession; it is the Lord's sacred inheritance, and Judah is His *cheleq* (portion) within it. The election language of 'He will again choose Jerusalem' re-activates what the exile had seemed to cancel — divine chosenness is not revoked by judgment but renewed by return.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shakhan* (dwell, 2:10-11) — tabernacle-language, the same root as *mishkan*. John 1:14 uses *eskēnōsen* (pitched His tent, dwelt) to describe the incarnation — the same semantic field deliberately invoked. *Admat ha-qodesh* (holy land, 2:12) — unique in the OT; the land's holiness is derived from the holy God who possesses it as His portion. *Lavah* (join themselves, 2:11) — clinging attachment, not loose association."
