        "body": "The chapter's final verse is its simplest and most profound. After the vision (2:1-5), the oracle of judgment (2:6-9), and the promise of dwelling and nations-gathering (2:10-12), the text commands universal silence: *hasah kol-basar mipney yehovah* — 'Hush, all flesh, from before the LORD.' The command is not merely liturgical; it is epistemological. All human words, plans, measurements, and arguments must stop when God moves. The measuring man of verse 1 represents all human activity before God's self-disclosure; verse 13 silences him.\n\nThe reason given is the divine arousal: 'He is aroused (*ur*) from His holy habitation.' The verb *ur* means to awaken, to rouse oneself for decisive action — it is the language of the divine warrior who had seemed to sleep through Israel's suffering (cf. Psalm 44:23, 'Arouse Yourself, why do You sleep, O Lord?'). The chapter answers that lament: the Lord has not been absent; He has been in His holy habitation. And now He is moving. The holy habitation (*ma'on qodsho*) is the heavenly throne-room — the same spatial anchor of Isaiah 6:1 and 1 Kings 22:19, where the Lord sits in sovereign council before His purposes break into history.\n\nThe doxological close places the entire chapter in proper perspective. All its extravagant promises — the wall of fire, the dwelling glory, the reversal of nations, the gathering of Gentiles — are not optimistic projections of a community hoping for the best. They are declarations of a God who is actively moving from His holy dwelling toward His city. The proper human response to such declarations is not analysis but awe. As John Calvin observed on this verse: 'Whenever God arises to execute judgment, all creatures ought to be still, that the majesty of his power may appear' (*Commentary on Zechariah*, 2:13). Habakkuk 2:20, Zephaniah 1:7, and Zechariah 2:13 form a canonical triad of this sacred silence — three witnesses to the same theological truth: when the sovereign God moves, all created speech stops.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Hasah* (be silent) — an onomatopoeic hush-word, the sound itself communicating the command. *Ur* (aroused) — awakening from apparent rest for purposeful action; the divine warrior's stirring posture. *Ma'on qodsho* (His holy habitation) — the heavenly dwelling place, not the earthly temple; God descends FROM His heavenly throne TO Jerusalem."
